"Seaton P.T., Hu H., Perner H., Pritchard H.W.","Ex situ conservation of Orchids in a warming world",2010,"Botanical Review","76","2",,"193","203",,,10.1007/s12229-010-9048-6,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77952425017&partnerID=40&md5=a3edf2d2a1f2383c89cc35d59ac72231","Seed Conservation Department, Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, Wakehurst Place, Ardingly, West Sussex RH17 6TN, United Kingdom; Kunming Institute of Botany, Chinese Academy of Sciences, 132 Lanhei Road, Kunming 650204 Yunnan, China; Sichuan Hengduan Mts Biotechnology, 3-11-904, Yinduhuayuan, Xinguang Rd.8, 610041 Chengdu, Sichuan, China","Seaton, P.T., Seed Conservation Department, Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, Wakehurst Place, Ardingly, West Sussex RH17 6TN, United Kingdom; Hu, H., Kunming Institute of Botany, Chinese Academy of Sciences, 132 Lanhei Road, Kunming 650204 Yunnan, China; Perner, H., Sichuan Hengduan Mts Biotechnology, 3-11-904, Yinduhuayuan, Xinguang Rd.8, 610041 Chengdu, Sichuan, China; Pritchard, H.W., Seed Conservation Department, Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, Wakehurst Place, Ardingly, West Sussex RH17 6TN, United Kingdom","Whilst there is overwhelming scientific evidence that dramatic changes in regional climates are likely to occur throughout the 21st century, the scientific community remains uncertain how the effects of global heating will combine with other environmental factors to affect wild orchid populations. It is, however, likely that many populations will be affected adversely and that in situ conservation techniques by themselves will not be sufficient to prevent the extinction of many species. A range of complimentary ex situ strategies are discussed. Amongst these orchid seed banking has been shown to be an invaluable tool for conserving the maximum amount of genetic diversity in the minimum space and has the potential to enable the conservation of valuable material for possible re-introduction and habitat restoration programmes in the future. The Darwin Initiative project, 'Orchid Seed Stores for Sustainable Use' (OSSSU), is currently establishing a global network of orchid seed banks focussing initially on countries with high orchid biodiversity in Asia and Latin America. Particular reference is made to ex situ conservation in China, together with the urgent need to gather more data to determine which habitats and species are most at risk of extinction in the wild in the immediate future. © The New York Botanical Garden 2010.","China; Global Warming; Living Collections; Orchids; Seed Storage","Orchidaceae",,,,,,"Report of the International Orchid Commission (1985) Proceedings of the 11th World Orchid Conference 1984, pp. 62-64. , Miami, Florida, Anonymous, K. W. Tan (Ed.), Singapore: International Press Company; Batty, A.L., Dixon, K.W., Brundrett, M., Sivasithamparam, K., Long-term storage of mycorrhizal fungi and seed as a tool for the conservation of Western Australian terrestrial orchids (2001) Australian Journal of Botany, 49, pp. 1-10; Benzing, D., Vascular Epiphytes (2004) Forest Canopies, pp. 175-211. , In: M. D. Lowman & H. D. Rinker (eds), 2nd Edition. Elsevier Academic Press; Libro Rojo de Plantas de Colombia (2007) Volumen 6: Orquideas primer parte, , Calderon-Saenz E. (ed)., Instituto Alexander von Humboldt-Ministerio de Ambiente, Vivienda y Desarrollo; Cribb, P.J., (1998) The Genus Paphiopedilum, , Kota Kinabalu: Natural History Publications (Borneo); Cribb, P.J., Kell, S.P., Dixon, K.W., Barrett, R.L., Orchid Conservation: A global perspective (2003) Orchid Conservation, pp. 1-25. , K. W. Dixon, S. P. Kell, R. L. Barrett, and P. J. Cribb (Eds.), Kota Kinabalu, Sabah: Natural History Publicatons; Cueva, A., González, Y., In vitro germination and somatic embryogenesis induction in Cyrtochilum loxense, an endemic and vulnerable orchid from Ecuador (2009) Proceedings of the Second Scientific Conference on Andean Orchids, pp. 56-62. , In: A. Pridgeon & J. P. Suarez (eds); Dixon, K.W., Batty, A.L., Integrat